    "narrative": "LawDog\u2019s lineup for April 21st hinges on two high-leverage spots: **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** and **Daulton Varsho**. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** leads the team with a 79.37 efficiency score, feasting on a soft matchup against Weiss (6.50 xERA). His ability to anchor the 3-hole against a weak arm makes him our primary anchor. Meanwhile, **Daulton Varsho** (70.29) is the day\u2019s premier value play; despite facing an elite hold pitcher in Kochanowicz, the +19% SP skill adjustment and +10% platoon boost highlight his utility in a favorable environment. We also see strong performance from **Gleyber Torres** (63.57) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (62.94), both of whom benefit from positive park factors and favorable platoon splits, serving as the engine for our middle-infield production today.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved keeping **Jonathan Aranda** on the bench at a 46.30 score. While his xwOBA (0.382) suggests he is hitting the ball hard, the matchup against Burns (2.76 xERA) is a clear deterrent, resulting in a -19% SP skill penalty that suppressed his efficiency below the threshold of our starters. Similarly, we are managing risk with our C1 spot; **Yainer Diaz** (44.51) remains in the lineup despite a tough draw against Messick, as we lack a more efficient alternative to maintain our daily game cap efficiency. \n\nInvestors should monitor the heavy concentration of our team against Yamamoto, who faces **Luis Arraez**, **Matt Chapman**, **Jung Hoo Lee**, and **Drew Gilbert**. The negative 16% SP skill adjustment across these players underscores the defensive nature of today\u2019s strategy; we are playing for contact and positional flexibility rather than power upside in those slots. While **Lawrence Butler** (55.53) provides some protection with his +13% platoon edge, owners should note that he faces a more formidable pitcher in Castillo, requiring us to prioritize consistent plate appearances over pure ceiling tonight.",
